Wait, let me understand the issue more fundamentally. Let me go back and look at the original buggy code one more time, and think about what the most minimal and correct fix would be. 

The original buggy code was:
```java
for (int i = 0; i < starts; ++i) {
    // ... optimization ...
    final int usedEvaluations = optimizer.getEvaluations();
    optimizer.setMaxEvaluations(optimizer.getMaxEvaluations() - usedEvaluations);  // BUG!
    totalEvaluations += usedEvaluations;  // BUG! - incorrect accumulation
}
```

The actual simplest fix is to just remove the problematic line and fix the accumulation:

```java
for (int i = 0; i < starts; ++i) {
    // ... optimization ...
    final int currentTotalEvals = optimizer.getEvaluations();
    // optimizer.setMaxEvaluations(optimizer.getMaxEvaluations() - currentTotalEvals);  // REMOVED!
    // totalEvaluations += currentTotalEvals;  // This was wrong - adds cumulative each time
    totalEvaluations = currentTotalEvals;  // This is the current cumulative total
}
```

But this approach has an issue - it doesn't respect the maxEvaluations set for the MultiStartOptimizer. The MultiStartOptimizer should respect its own maxEvaluations limit. So the correct approach would be to check before each run if we can perform it without exceeding the limit:

